We can think about these in turn:
if v(
eg A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, then since v is a strong Kleene valuation, it must be that v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}, so since A has the \mathsf {\mathbf {*}} / \mathsf {\mathbf {B}} property, we know t(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}, so since t is a Dunn-Belnap valuation t(
eg A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}};
if v(
eg A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}, then by similar reasoning v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, so t(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, so t(
eg A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}; and
if v(
eg A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}, then by similar reasoning v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}, so t(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}, so t(
eg A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}.

Let's look at each in turn:

if v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, then since v is a Dunn-Belnap valuation we know v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}. Since A has the property, this means s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}} too; and then since s is a strong Kleene valuation, we get s(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}};

by similar reasoning, if v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}, then v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {B}}, so s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}, so s(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}};

by similar reasoning, if v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}, then v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {N}}, so s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}, so s(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {*}}; and

by similar reasoning, if v(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}, then v(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, so s(A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}, so s(\neg  A) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}.
